=========================================
C++ UNORDERED_MAP (HASH TABLE) - STL NOTES
=========================================

1. What is std::unordered_map?
-------------------------------
std::unordered_map is an associative container that stores:
(key, value) pairs with UNIQUE keys.

It does NOT maintain any order of keys.

Example:
unordered_map<int, string> um;

um[2] = "two";
um[1] = "one";

Output order is NOT guaranteed:
1 -> "one"
2 -> "two"
(or any random order)

-----------------------------------------
2. Internal Implementation
-----------------------------------------
std::unordered_map is implemented using:

👉 HASH TABLE

Structure:
- Array of buckets
- Hash function maps key → bucket index
- Each bucket stores entries (collision handled internally)

Example:

key → hash(key) → index → bucket

-----------------------------------------
3. Why Hash Table?
-----------------------------------------
Because it provides:

✔ O(1) average time for insert
✔ O(1) average time for search
✔ O(1) average time for delete

BUT:
❌ Worst case can become O(n) due to collisions

-----------------------------------------
4. Key Properties
-----------------------------------------
- Stores unique keys
- No ordering of keys
- Faster than map (average case)
- Uses hash function
- Allows custom hash function

-----------------------------------------
5. Time Complexities
-----------------------------------------
Operation        Complexity
--------------------------------
insert           O(1) avg, O(n) worst
erase            O(1) avg, O(n) worst
find             O(1) avg, O(n) worst
operator[]       O(1) avg, O(n) worst

-----------------------------------------
6. Hash Function
-----------------------------------------
Internal process:

key → hash_function(key) → bucket_index

Example:
hash(10) % bucket_size = index

Collisions handled using:
- chaining (linked list / list inside bucket)

-----------------------------------------
