-----------------------------------------
8. insert() vs operator[]
-----------------------------------------

insert():
- Inserts only if key NOT present
- Does NOT overwrite

um.insert({1, "A"});

operator[]:
- Inserts if key not present
- Overwrites if key exists

um[1] = "A";

-----------------------------------------
9. find() Function
-----------------------------------------
Returns iterator if found
Else returns end()

if(um.find(10) != um.end())
    cout << "Found";

-----------------------------------------
10. Iterator Behavior
-----------------------------------------
VERY IMPORTANT:

✔ Iterators are NOT sorted
✔ Order can change after insert/erase
✔ Rehash can invalidate ALL iterators

-----------------------------------------
11. Rehashing
-----------------------------------------
When bucket load increases:

👉 rehash happens

Effects:
- Bucket size increases
- Elements redistributed
- ALL iterators become INVALID

-----------------------------------------
12. map vs unordered_map
-----------------------------------------

map (Red-Black Tree):
- O(log n)
- Sorted keys
- Stable ordering

unordered_map (Hash Table):
- O(1) average
- No order
- Faster in most cases

-----------------------------------------
13. When to use unordered_map?
-----------------------------------------
Use when:
✔ Need fast lookup
✔ Order not required
✔ Frequency counting problems
✔ Hash-based problems

Avoid when:
✗ Need sorted output
✗ Need range queries (use map)

-----------------------------------------
14. Real-world Use Cases
-----------------------------------------
- Frequency counting
- Caching (LRU concepts)
- Index mapping
- Lookup tables
- Competitive programming hashing problems

